[1
Date: Wed 24 Jan 2001 10:41:48 -0500
From: Dan Bausch <dsb8@cdc.gov>

Comment on Case Fatality Rates in the Ugandan Outbreak
------------------------------------------------------
I feel compelled to comment on the case fatality rates that are
frequently quoted for the recent Ebola hemorrhagic fever outbreak in
Uganda. A recent report mentioned that: "While in past Ebola
outbreaks up to 90 percent of victims died, Ugandan doctors and
international health experts have been able to save 60 percent of the
patients by using aggressive rehydration therapy."
We have to be careful to compare case fatality rates between epidemics
of the same strain. The epidemic in Uganda, caused by the Sudan
strain, should not be compared to the Kikwit epidemic caused by the
Zaire strain, which is considered more virulent and for which case
fatality rates are posted at up to 90%.
The Ugandan epidemic is more appropriately compared to the
outbreaks of the Ebola Sudan strain that occurred in Sudan in 1976 and
1979. These had case fatality rates in the 55-60% range.
We'll have to see how things look when we get all the data together, but
it's not clear that we've made big improvements in clinical care since
the 1970's. Preliminary data from one of the Ebola fever wards in Gulu
show a case fatality rate among confirmed cases of 58%.
Aggressive hydration certainly is important in treating Ebola fever, and
I don't doubt that it can, on occasion, save someone's life. While I
know that all of us involved in clinical care in Gulu did the best [we
could, Ebola fever can be a very aggressive disease. I wish that it was
otherwise, but I suspect that rehydration alone is unlikely to make a
huge difference in mortality.
--
Daniel G. Bausch, MD, MPH
Special Pathogens Branch, MS G-14
Division of Viral and Rickettsial Diseases
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
1600 Clifton Rd.
Atlanta GA 30333 USA
<dsb8@cdc.gov>
[Special thanks to Daniel for giving us the view from the trenches. -
Mod.JW
