Date: Wed 24 Jan 2001 10:27:30 -0500
From: John Finerty (NCI) <finertyj@dcbdcep1.nci.nih.gov>

Suggestions for Follow-up Studies
---------------------------------
With the apparent end of the Ebola hemorrhagic fever outbreak in
Uganda and the high number of survivors, there seems to be an
opportunity to gain some valuable information regarding patient
responses. Has serum from patients been frozen? How about drawn
bloods from survivors to obtain serum samples for assays? Antibody
profiles, particularly allotype, isotype and epitope specificities could be
revealing.
I realize that working with these samples is risky, and use of the virus
as antigen(s) extremely so, yet the data may give us some important
epidemiologic data. If there is a particular protein/peptide that is
immunogenic in survivors -- as evidenced by antibody response as a
start -- this could, by DNA/amino acid sequence, provide a tool for
further study.
Studies of this nature may be ongoing and I hope the data will be made
available to the biomedical community at the earliest opportunity.
--
John F. Finerty, Ph.D.
Cellular Immunology & AIDS Lymphoma Section
Cancer Immunology & Hematology Branch
National Cancer Institute, NIH
EPN, Rm. 5060
6130 Executive Boulevard
Rockville, MD 20852
<fin@nih.gov>
[Both preceding comments highlight some topics for post-outbreak
research and analysis. Those involved in the control and containment
of the outbreak deserve some respite from their labors in order to take
stock of the situation and to establish the immediate priorities. In the
meantime all those involved deserve our congratulations. - Mod.CP
